lines.text: Look, I swear Paris will be prayed for (Prayed for)
Unreleased Off-White to the ankles, ayy (Ankles)

annotations.text:
The company responsible for creating Off-white shoes was first founded as “PYREX VISION” by Virgil Abloh in Milan, Italy in 2012. Abloh then rebranded the company as Off-White in 2013, which he described as “the grey area between black and white as the color off-white” to the fashion world.

The song itself is about the luxuries their (their being Gunn, Joey, Tyler, and Billie) careers have afforded. Billie talking about unreleased shoes is one of the elements of this songs that talks about their luxuries.

lines.text: I'm in them places that you can't go (That you can't go)

annotations.text:
In keeping with the larger themes of both the song and the album, these lines highlight the high-end exclusivity of the Paris fashion world.

“Don C,” short for Don Crawley, currently runs his own street-wear brand Just Don as well as partnering with Virgil Abloh on the RSVP Gallery. “Nigo” is Tomoaki Nagao,  founder A Bathing Ape, or Bape for short. Nigo has worked with Pharrell Williams and Kanye West on street-wear projects like Billionaire Boys Club and Ice Cream footwear. Having both of these iconic designers sitting in the same row indicates the significance of the event, one that Gunn also gets to enjoy since he is also in “them places that you can’t go.”

annotations.text:
Tyler’s sitting in the backseat listening to “Frontin'” by Pharrell Williams featuring JAY-Z. This shouldn’t be a surprise as Tyler has publicly cited Pharrell and his band N.E.R.D as his biggest influence over and over again.



Also, throughout the years, they have collaborated on many songs: for example, Pusha T’s “Trouble on My Mind”, Frank Ocean’s “End/Golden Girl” (both co-produced by Pharrell and featuring Tyler), and Tyler’s own songs “IFHY” (2013), “KEEP DA O’S” (2015), “Enjoy Right Now, Today” (2017) and “ARE WE STILL FRIENDS?” (2019).

Plus, on his song “I THINK,” included in his 2019 album IGOR, Tyler might have paid further homage to Pharrell by making an intro similar to Williams' signature “four-count” start, even though fans have considered the song to be mainly “Kanye-inspired”.
